  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a Token Tax?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **Token Tax** is a fee automatically taken when a cryptocurrency token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nIt is usually built into the token’s smart contract. For example, if a token has a **5% tax** and you sell 100 tokens, 5 tokens may be deducted and used for specific purposes.\n\nCommon uses of token taxes include:\n\n- **Burning tokens** to reduce supply\n- **Adding liquidity** to a trading pool\n- **Rewarding holders** with reflections or redistributions\n- **Funding marketing or development**\n- **Sending funds to a project treasury**\n\nExample:\n\n> A token has a 10% sell tax.  \n> If you sell $1,000 worth of the token, $100 is taken as tax and $900 is effectively sold.\n\nToken taxes are common in DeFi and meme coins. They can be legitimate, but high or changeable taxes can also be a red flag because they may make it expensive or difficult to sell the token.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **Token Tax** usually refers to a built-in fee charged when someone **buys, sells, or transfers a crypto token**.\n\nFor example, a token might have a **5% sell tax**, meaning if you sell $100 worth of the token, $5 is automatically taken by the smart contract.\n\nThat fee may be used for things like:\n\n- **Liquidity** — adding funds to a trading pool\n- **Rewards/reflections** — redistributing tokens to holders\n- **Burns** — permanently removing tokens from supply\n- **Treasury/marketing** — funding the project team or ecosystem\n- **Development** — paying for future project work\n\nExample:\n\n> A token has a 3% buy tax and 7% sell tax.  \n> If you buy $1,000 worth, $30 is taken as tax.  \n> If you later sell $1,000 worth, $70 is taken as tax.\n\nImportantly, a **token tax is not the same as government tax**. It is usually a project-level transaction fee coded into the token’s smart contract.\n\nIn crypto, high token taxes can be a warning sign because they may make it expensive to exit a position or may be used by scam projects to extract value from traders. Always check the token contract, tax rates, and whether the team can change the tax later.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from token cost / API cost-per-token?",
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from bloat / overhead?",
    "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from cognitive load (in notation design)?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "“Token Tax” and “token cost / API cost-per-token” are completely different concepts that use the word **token** in different contexts.\n\n| Term | Context | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Cryptocurrency / DeFi | A fee charged when buying, selling, or transferring a crypto token |\n| **Token cost / API cost-per-token** | AI / APIs / LLMs | The price charged for processing text tokens through an API |\n\n### Token Tax\n\nA **Token Tax** applies to crypto assets.\n\nExample:\n\n> You sell 1,000 crypto tokens with a 5% sell tax.  \n> 50 tokens are deducted, and you effectively sell 950 tokens.\n\nThe tax is usually enforced by the token’s smart contract and may be used for liquidity, burns, rewards, treasury funding, or development.\n\n### API cost-per-token\n\nAn **API cost-per-token** applies to AI model usage.\n\nIn AI APIs, a “token” is a chunk of text, such as a word, part of a word, punctuation, or symbol.\n\nExample:\n\n> You send a prompt with 1,000 input tokens and receive 500 output tokens.  \n> The API provider charges you based on those 1,500 processed tokens.\n\nThis is not a tax. It is a usage-based fee, similar to paying per byte of data, per API call, or per compute unit.\n\n### Simple distinction\n\nA **Token Tax** is:\n\n> A crypto transaction fee built into a blockchain token.\n\nAn **API cost-per-token** is:\n\n> A pricing unit for processing text or data with an API.\n\nSo despite the similar wording, they are unrelated. One is about **crypto trading mechanics**, and the other is about **software/API billing**.",
    "“Token Tax” and “bloat / overhead” can sound similar because both can describe an added cost, but they mean different things.\n\n| Term | Main context | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Crypto / DeFi | A deliberate fee deducted when a crypto token is bought, sold, or transferred |\n| **Bloat / overhead** | Software, APIs, systems, prompts | Extra size, work, complexity, or cost that is not central to the main task |\n\n### Token Tax\n\nA **Token Tax** is an explicit, usually intentional fee built into a crypto token’s smart contract.\n\nExample:\n\n> You sell 1,000 tokens with a 5% token tax.  \n> 50 tokens are deducted automatically.\n\nThat deducted amount may go to liquidity, burns, rewards, a treasury, or project funding.\n\nSo a token tax is:\n\n> A designed transaction fee on a crypto token.\n\n### Bloat / overhead\n\n**Bloat** or **overhead** is extra resource usage that may not directly contribute to the desired result.\n\nIn an API or AI context, overhead might include:\n\n- Extra prompt text\n- Repeated instructions\n- Large schemas\n- Verbose metadata\n- Unnecessary context\n- Formatting wrappers\n- System or tool messages\n- Boilerplate responses\n\nExample:\n\n> You only need to ask, “Summarize this paragraph,” but your request includes 2,000 extra tokens of instructions, formatting rules, and unused context.\n\nThose extra tokens are **overhead** or **bloat** because they increase cost and latency without necessarily improving the output.\n\n### Key difference\n\nA **Token Tax** is a specific fee mechanism:\n\n> “Every transaction loses X% by design.”\n\n**Bloat / overhead** is excess usage or inefficiency:\n\n> “This request or system uses more resources than necessary.”\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nIf API usage is like shipping a package:\n\n- **Token cost** = the shipping company charges by weight.\n- **Bloat / overhead** = extra packing material that makes the package heavier.\n- **Token tax** = a separate fee automatically taken from a crypto transaction.\n\nSo, token tax is not the same as bloat. A token tax is an intentional crypto fee, while bloat/overhead is unnecessary or auxiliary resource usage that increases cost or complexity.",
    "“Token Tax” and **cognitive load in notation design** are different kinds of “cost.”\n\n| Term | Context | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Crypto / DeFi | A fee deducted when a crypto token is bought, sold, or transferred |\n| **Cognitive load** | Notation / language / interface design | The mental effort required to read, understand, remember, or use a notation |\n\n### Token Tax\n\nA **Token Tax** is a concrete transaction fee.\n\nExample:\n\n> A crypto token has a 5% sell tax.  \n> If you sell 1,000 tokens, 50 tokens are deducted automatically.\n\nIt is usually encoded in a smart contract and has a financial effect.\n\n### Cognitive load in notation design\n\n**Cognitive load** is about how hard a notation is to understand or use.\n\nA notation has high cognitive load if it requires users to:\n\n- Remember many symbols or rules\n- Mentally translate between forms\n- Track hidden state or implicit behavior\n- Parse dense or unfamiliar syntax\n- Hold too many details in working memory\n- Infer meaning from context rather than seeing it directly\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nx |> f |> g |> h\n```\n\nmay be easy for someone familiar with pipeline notation, but confusing to someone who has never seen it.\n\nAnother example:\n\n```text\n∀x∈S, ∃y∈T : R(x,y)\n```\n\nis compact, but it imposes more cognitive load on readers unfamiliar with mathematical logic notation.\n\n### Key difference\n\nA **Token Tax** is a financial/mechanical cost:\n\n> “Each crypto transaction loses X%.”\n\n**Cognitive load** is a human comprehension cost:\n\n> “This notation takes mental effort to understand or use correctly.”\n\n### Simple analogy\n\nIf notation is like a road sign:\n\n- **Token tax** would be like a toll booth that charges you money.\n- **Cognitive load** would be like a confusing sign that takes longer to interpret.\n\nSo, a token tax is an explicit fee in a crypto system, while cognitive load is the mental burden created by design choices in notation, syntax, or representation."
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"Token Tax\": Token Tax names the explicit token-overhead cost a structured notation pays in exchange for structural integrity, auditability, and reasoning headroom — reframing that overhead from \"waste\" to \"tax\": a price paid for benefits (line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, freed reasoning budget, audit-grade provenance) that block-format brevity does not deliver. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I’ve read the canonical definition:\n\n**Token Tax** refers to the explicit token-overhead cost a structured notation pays in exchange for benefits like structural integrity, auditability, reasoning headroom, line-oriented partial-validity, type enforcement, and audit-grade provenance—reframing that overhead not as waste, but as a tax paid for capabilities that terse block formats do not provide.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "**Token Tax** differs from **token cost / API cost-per-token** in that they refer to different layers:\n\n### 1. Token cost / API cost-per-token\n\nThis is the **literal monetary billing rate** charged by an AI/API provider.\n\nExample:\n\n> An API charges $X per million input tokens and $Y per million output tokens.\n\nThis is an economic usage cost. It answers:\n\n> “How much money do these tokens cost to process?”\n\n---\n\n### 2. Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is the **extra token overhead introduced by a structured notation or format** in exchange for useful properties.\n\nExample:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"age\": 30,\n  \"role\": \"admin\"\n}\n```\n\nuses more tokens than:\n\n```text\nAlice 30 admin\n```\n\nThe additional braces, quotes, keys, colons, commas, and line structure are the **Token Tax**.\n\nBut that overhead buys benefits such as:\n\n- clearer structure\n- type enforcement\n- easier validation\n- partial line-by-line readability\n- better auditability\n- better provenance tracking\n- reduced reasoning ambiguity\n- easier machine parsing\n\nSo Token Tax answers:\n\n> “How many extra tokens does this notation spend to gain structure, safety, and reasoning clarity?”\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **API cost-per-token** | The provider’s monetary price for processing tokens |\n| **Token Tax** | The representational overhead paid by a format to gain structural benefits |\n\nThey are related because Token Tax can increase API cost, but they are not the same thing.\n\nA structured notation may have a higher **Token Tax**, which means more tokens, which may then result in higher **API cost**. But the Token Tax is about the **design tradeoff**, not the billing rate itself.",
    "**Token Tax** differs from **bloat** or generic **overhead** mainly in framing, justification, and payoff.\n\n### 1. Bloat\n\n**Bloat** means extra tokens or complexity that do **not** provide enough value.\n\nIt implies waste.\n\nExample:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"user_profile_information_record\": {\n    \"user_profile_information_record_name_field\": \"Alice\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nIf the verbosity does not improve validation, auditability, clarity, or reasoning, it is just bloat.\n\nBloat answers:\n\n> “Why is this so unnecessarily large?”\n\n---\n\n### 2. Overhead\n\n**Overhead** is a neutral term for extra cost added by a representation, protocol, or process.\n\nIt may be useful or wasteful.\n\nExample:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"age\": 30\n}\n```\n\nThe braces, quotes, field names, and punctuation are overhead compared with:\n\n```text\nAlice 30\n```\n\nOverhead answers:\n\n> “What extra machinery does this format require?”\n\n---\n\n### 3. Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is a specific kind of overhead: explicit token overhead paid in exchange for structural benefits.\n\nIt is not “extra tokens are good.” Rather, it says:\n\n> “These extra tokens are a price paid for integrity, validation, auditability, provenance, and reasoning headroom.”\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nname: Alice\nage: 30\nrole: admin\n```\n\nThis is longer than:\n\n```text\nAlice 30 admin\n```\n\nBut the extra tokens buy clearer field identity, easier parsing, partial validity, and reduced ambiguity.\n\n---\n\n### Key distinction\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Value judgment |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bloat** | Unnecessary excess | Negative |\n| **Overhead** | Extra representational cost | Neutral |\n| **Token Tax** | Justified overhead paid for structural guarantees and reasoning benefits | Positive or at least defensible |\n\nSo:\n\n> **All Token Tax is overhead, but not all overhead is Token Tax.**  \n> **Bloat is overhead that fails to justify itself.**\n\nThe term **Token Tax** is useful because it forces the question:\n\n> “What benefits are these extra tokens buying?”\n\nIf the answer is structural integrity, auditability, type enforcement, partial-validity, provenance, or reduced reasoning burden, then it may be a legitimate Token Tax.\n\nIf the answer is “nothing meaningful,” then it is probably just bloat.",
    "**Token Tax** differs from **cognitive load** because they measure different kinds of cost.\n\n### 1. Cognitive load\n\n**Cognitive load** is the mental effort required for a human or model to understand, manipulate, or verify a notation.\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “How hard is this to read, reason about, and use correctly?”\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nAlice 30 admin true 2024-01-01\n```\n\nThis is compact, but it may impose cognitive load because the reader has to remember what each position means.\n\nIs `true` active status? Verified status? Admin flag? Something else?\n\n---\n\n### 2. Token Tax\n\n**Token Tax** is the extra token cost introduced by a structured notation in exchange for benefits like structural integrity, type enforcement, auditability, provenance, partial validity, and reasoning headroom.\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “How many extra tokens are being spent to make the structure explicit and safer to reason over?”\n\nExample:\n\n```yaml\nname: Alice\nage: 30\nrole: admin\nactive: true\ncreated_at: 2024-01-01\n```\n\nThis has a higher Token Tax than the compact positional version, but it likely reduces cognitive load because the fields are explicit.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | What it measures | Primary domain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Extra representational token cost | Notation / format / API context |\n| **Cognitive load** | Mental effort required to understand or reason | Human/model cognition |\n\nThey are related, but not identical.\n\nA notation can have:\n\n### Low Token Tax, high cognitive load\n\n```text\nA 30 X T 01\n```\n\nVery compact, but unclear.\n\n### High Token Tax, low cognitive load\n\n```json\n{\n  \"name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"age\": 30,\n  \"role\": \"admin\",\n  \"active\": true,\n  \"created_month\": \"January\"\n}\n```\n\nMore tokens, but easier to interpret and audit.\n\n### High Token Tax, high cognitive load\n\n```json\n{\n  \"usr_prof_meta_ident_record\": {\n    \"nm_val\": \"Alice\",\n    \"ag_int\": 30,\n    \"rl_cd\": \"X\",\n    \"flg_01\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\nVerbose and still confusing. That may be bloat, not a useful Token Tax.\n\n---\n\nSo the distinction is:\n\n> **Cognitive load is the mental burden of understanding. Token Tax is the token-level price paid by a notation.**\n\nA well-designed notation may deliberately pay a **Token Tax** to reduce **cognitive load** and improve reasoning, validation, and auditability. But paying more tokens does not automatically reduce cognitive load; the extra structure has to buy something meaningful."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **Token Tax** usually refers to a fee or tax associated with a cryptocurrency or blockchain token. The meaning depends on context:\n\n1. **Token transaction tax in crypto projects**  \n   Some tokens have a built-in fee on buys, sells, or transfers. For example, a token might charge a 5% tax whenever it is traded. That fee may be used for:\n   - Burning tokens to reduce supply\n   - Funding liquidity pools\n   - Rewarding holders\n   - Supporting project development or marketing\n   - Sending funds to a treasury wallet\n\n   Example: If you sell $100 worth of a token with a 5% token tax, $5 is taken as the tax and you receive $95 before other exchange or network fees.\n\n2. **Government tax on token transactions**  \n   “Token tax” can also mean taxes owed to a government when you trade, sell, earn, or receive crypto tokens. Depending on the country, tokens may be taxed as:\n   - Capital gains\n   - Income\n   - Business revenue\n   - Sales or transaction-related tax\n\n3. **NFT or in-game token fees**  \n   In gaming or NFT ecosystems, a token tax may be a platform fee charged when tokens or digital assets are bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nIn short, a **Token Tax** is either a built-in blockchain fee applied to token activity or a government tax obligation related to owning or trading tokens.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "A **Token Tax** is different from **token cost** or **API cost-per-token** because they refer to different kinds of “tokens.”\n\n### 1. Token Tax: usually crypto/blockchain-related\n\nA **Token Tax** usually means a fee or tax applied to a cryptocurrency or blockchain token transaction.\n\nExample:\n\n- You buy or sell a crypto token.\n- The token contract charges a 5% transaction tax.\n- If you sell $100 worth, $5 is taken as the token tax.\n\nThis is common in crypto projects where the fee may fund liquidity, rewards, burns, or a project treasury.\n\nIt can also mean government tax owed on crypto activity, such as capital gains or income tax.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Token cost / API cost-per-token: AI/API usage pricing\n\n**API cost-per-token** refers to how AI providers charge for text processed by a model.\n\nIn AI systems, a “token” is a chunk of text, such as a word, part of a word, punctuation mark, or symbol.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Hello world”\n\nmight be counted as 2 tokens, while a longer sentence may be 10–20 tokens.\n\nAPI pricing is often based on:\n\n- **Input tokens**: text you send to the model\n- **Output tokens**: text the model generates back\n- Sometimes **cached tokens**, **reasoning tokens**, or other categories depending on the provider\n\nExample:\n\nIf an AI API costs `$1 per 1 million input tokens` and you send 10,000 input tokens, your input cost would be:\n\n> 10,000 / 1,000,000 × $1 = $0.01\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Term | Domain | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Crypto/blockchain | A fee or tax on crypto token transactions, or government tax on token-related activity |\n| **Token cost / API cost-per-token** | AI/API pricing | The price charged for processing text tokens through an API |\n\nSo, **Token Tax is about financial or blockchain transaction fees**, while **API cost-per-token is about usage-based pricing for processing text with an AI model**.",
    "A **Token Tax** differs from **bloat** or **overhead** mainly in what it describes:\n\n| Term | Meaning | Usually implies |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | An extra cost or penalty associated with using tokens | A measurable cost, fee, or recurring token burden |\n| **Overhead** | Extra resources required to make a system work | Often necessary or structural |\n| **Bloat** | Unnecessary extra size, complexity, or content | Usually wasteful or avoidable |\n\n### In API / AI usage terms\n\nIf someone says **“token tax”** in an AI/API context, they usually mean the **extra tokens you must spend beyond the core user content**.\n\nFor example, an API call may include:\n\n- System prompts\n- Developer instructions\n- Tool definitions\n- JSON schemas\n- Conversation history\n- Safety instructions\n- Formatting requirements\n\nThose tokens are not the user’s actual question, but they still count toward cost and context length.\n\nThat extra usage can be called a **token tax**.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nUser question: 20 tokens\nSystem prompt + tool schema + formatting rules: 800 tokens\n```\n\nThe 800 tokens are the “tax” you pay to use the model in that structured way.\n\n---\n\n### How that differs from overhead\n\n**Overhead** is the broader technical term.\n\nOverhead means additional cost required to operate the system.\n\nFor example:\n\n- HTTP headers\n- Authentication metadata\n- Prompt wrappers\n- Tool schemas\n- Logging\n- Serialization\n- Conversation memory\n\nSome overhead may be unavoidable.\n\nSo:\n\n> **Token tax is a token-specific form of overhead.**\n\nAll token tax is overhead, but not all overhead is token tax.\n\n---\n\n### How that differs from bloat\n\n**Bloat** means unnecessary excess.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\nPlease answer the user's question.\nPlease be helpful.\nPlease be clear.\nPlease be accurate.\nPlease make sure your answer is useful.\nPlease do not be unhelpful.\nPlease provide helpful information.\n```\n\nThis is prompt bloat because much of it is redundant.\n\nIf this redundant text increases token usage, it creates a **token tax**.\n\nSo:\n\n> **Bloat is often a cause of token tax.**\n\nBut token tax can also come from necessary things, like a required JSON schema or safety instruction.\n\n---\n\n### Simple distinction\n\n- **Overhead** = extra stuff needed to run the system.\n- **Bloat** = extra stuff that probably should not be there.\n- **Token tax** = the token cost caused by extra stuff, whether necessary or unnecessary.\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose your actual task needs only 100 tokens, but your API request includes:\n\n```text\n100 tokens: actual user request\n500 tokens: required system instructions\n1,200 tokens: tool/function schema\n700 tokens: unnecessary repeated prompt text\n```\n\nThen:\n\n- The **500 + 1,200** tokens are mostly **overhead**.\n- The **700** repeated tokens are **bloat**.\n- The total extra **2,400 tokens** are the **token tax** you pay.",
    "In **notation design**, **Token Tax** and **cognitive load** are related, but they are not the same thing.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token Tax** = the extra visible notation you must write or read.\n- **Cognitive load** = the mental effort required to understand, remember, or use the notation.\n\nA notation can have a high token tax but low cognitive load, or low token tax but high cognitive load.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Token Tax: extra syntactic cost\n\nIn notation design, a **token tax** is the amount of extra syntax required to express something.\n\nIt is about the **surface form**: characters, symbols, keywords, punctuation, wrappers, delimiters, boilerplate, etc.\n\nFor example:\n\n```js\nfunction add(a, b) {\n  return a + b;\n}\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```haskell\nadd a b = a + b\n```\n\nThe JavaScript version has more syntactic tokens: `function`, parentheses, braces, `return`, semicolon. Some of that is useful structure; some may feel like tax depending on the design goals.\n\nToken tax asks:\n\n> How much notation must the user pay before they can express the core idea?\n\n---\n\n## 2. Cognitive load: mental effort\n\n**Cognitive load** is about how hard the notation is to understand or work with.\n\nIt includes things like:\n\n- How much the reader has to remember\n- Whether symbols are intuitive\n- Whether precedence rules are obvious\n- Whether similar things look similar\n- Whether different things are visually distinguishable\n- Whether the notation matches the user’s mental model\n- Whether errors are easy to spot\n- Whether meaning is local or depends on distant context\n\nFor example:\n\n```apl\n(+/⍵)÷⍴⍵\n```\n\nThis may be very low in token count, but high in cognitive load for someone unfamiliar with APL-style notation.\n\nBy contrast:\n\n```python\nsum(values) / len(values)\n```\n\nuses more tokens, but is probably easier for many programmers to understand.\n\n---\n\n## Key difference\n\n| Concept | Measures | Main question |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Amount of extra syntax | “How much notation do I have to write/read?” |\n| **Cognitive load** | Mental effort | “How hard is this to understand/use correctly?” |\n\n---\n\n## They often interact, but not always\n\n### High token tax can increase cognitive load\n\nVerbose notation can make the reader work harder by adding clutter.\n\nExample:\n\n```xml\n<person>\n  <name>Ada</name>\n  <age>36</age>\n</person>\n```\n\nCompared with:\n\n```json\n{ \"name\": \"Ada\", \"age\": 36 }\n```\n\nThe XML version has more repeated closing tags. That extra syntax can create visual noise and increase cognitive load.\n\n---\n\n### Low token tax can increase cognitive load\n\nVery compact notation can be harder to understand.\n\nExample:\n\n```regex\n^\\w+([-+.']\\w+)*@\\w+([-.]\\w+)*\\.\\w+([-.]\\w+)*$\n```\n\nThis is compact, but cognitively dense. It has a low-ish token footprint relative to what it does, but a high interpretation burden.\n\n---\n\n### High token tax can reduce cognitive load\n\nSometimes extra notation helps comprehension.\n\nExample:\n\n```python\nif user.is_admin:\n    delete_account()\n```\n\nis more verbose than a symbolic form like:\n\n```text\nuser.admin? -> delete!\n```\n\nBut the added words and structure may make the intent clearer.\n\nSimilarly, explicit labels can reduce ambiguity:\n\n```text\nrotate(angle: 90, axis: \"x\")\n```\n\nhas more tokens than:\n\n```text\nrotate(90, \"x\")\n```\n\nbut the labels reduce the mental effort of remembering argument order.\n\n---\n\n## Important distinction\n\nA **token tax** is paid by the notation.\n\nA **cognitive load** is paid by the human.\n\nToken tax is about syntactic quantity. Cognitive load is about interpretive difficulty.\n\nThey can correlate, but they are not equivalent.\n\n---\n\n## Example in notation design\n\nSuppose you are designing a configuration language.\n\n### Version A\n\n```yaml\nretry:\n  enabled: true\n  count: 3\n  delay_seconds: 5\n```\n\n### Version B\n\n```text\nretry true 3 5\n```\n\nVersion B has a lower token tax. It is shorter.\n\nBut Version A may have lower cognitive load because the meaning of each value is labeled. In Version B, the reader must remember that the arguments are ordered as:\n\n```text\nretry enabled count delay\n```\n\nSo the shorter notation saves tokens but shifts burden onto memory.\n\n---\n\n## Practical design rule\n\nGood notation design is not simply about minimizing tokens.\n\nThe goal is usually to minimize:\n\n> **total cost = token tax + cognitive load + error risk**\n\nSometimes you add tokens to reduce cognitive load. Sometimes you remove tokens to reduce clutter. The best design depends on the audience, frequency of use, and consequences of misunderstanding.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Token Tax** is a syntactic cost.\n- **Cognitive load** is a mental cost.\n- Good notation balances both."
  ],
  "chat_a_full": {
    "turns": [
      {
        "user": "What is a Token Tax?",
        "assistant": "A **Token Tax** is a fee automatically taken when a cryptocurrency token is bought, sold, or transferred.\n\nIt is usually built into the token’s smart contract. For example, if a token has a **5% tax** and you sell 100 tokens, 5 tokens may be deducted and used for specific purposes.\n\nCommon uses of token taxes include:\n\n- **Burning tokens** to reduce supply\n- **Adding liquidity** to a trading pool\n- **Rewarding holders** with reflections or redistributions\n- **Funding marketing or development**\n- **Sending funds to a project treasury**\n\nExample:\n\n> A token has a 10% sell tax.  \n> If you sell $1,000 worth of the token, $100 is taken as tax and $900 is effectively sold.\n\nToken taxes are common in DeFi and meme coins. They can be legitimate, but high or changeable taxes can also be a red flag because they may make it expensive or difficult to sell the token.",
