        "user": "How does \"Token Tax\" differ from token cost / API cost-per-token?",
        "assistant": "A **Token Tax** is different from **token cost** or **API cost-per-token** because they refer to different kinds of “tokens.”\n\n### 1. Token Tax: usually crypto/blockchain-related\n\nA **Token Tax** usually means a fee or tax applied to a cryptocurrency or blockchain token transaction.\n\nExample:\n\n- You buy or sell a crypto token.\n- The token contract charges a 5% transaction tax.\n- If you sell $100 worth, $5 is taken as the token tax.\n\nThis is common in crypto projects where the fee may fund liquidity, rewards, burns, or a project treasury.\n\nIt can also mean government tax owed on crypto activity, such as capital gains or income tax.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Token cost / API cost-per-token: AI/API usage pricing\n\n**API cost-per-token** refers to how AI providers charge for text processed by a model.\n\nIn AI systems, a “token” is a chunk of text, such as a word, part of a word, punctuation mark, or symbol.\n\nExample:\n\n> “Hello world”\n\nmight be counted as 2 tokens, while a longer sentence may be 10–20 tokens.\n\nAPI pricing is often based on:\n\n- **Input tokens**: text you send to the model\n- **Output tokens**: text the model generates back\n- Sometimes **cached tokens**, **reasoning tokens**, or other categories depending on the provider\n\nExample:\n\nIf an AI API costs `$1 per 1 million input tokens` and you send 10,000 input tokens, your input cost would be:\n\n> 10,000 / 1,000,000 × $1 = $0.01\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Term | Domain | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Token Tax** | Crypto/blockchain | A fee or tax on crypto token transactions, or government tax on token-related activity |\n| **Token cost / API cost-per-token** | AI/API pricing | The price charged for processing text tokens through an API |\n\nSo, **Token Tax is about financial or blockchain transaction fees**, while **API cost-per-token is about usage-based pricing for processing text with an AI model**.",
